Rating: 0
Delicious! I used a combination of yellow heirloom and vine ripe tomatoes. I didn't have red wine vinegar so used a high quality sherry vinegar instead. I also subbed the regular cucumber for lemon cucumber and the jalapeno for serrano. I also didn't have time to chill for 6 hours so I put into individual bowls and put in the freezer to chill while I made the main course and it was perfect. I garnished with cucumber and cilantro and zing! It was perfect. Main take-away: this is a great foundation recipe that can be altered liberally and still be great!

Rating: 4
I recently went to Michael's in Santa Monica and sat outside on the patio and thoroughly enjoyed his spicy gazpacho! I came home, found this recipe, doubled the jalapeno pepper and, to my memory, it was really close to his remarkable soup. I even floated a little minced cucumber and shrimp with a cilantro leaf on a round tortilla just (hidden just beneath the surface)...for an artistic garnish! fantastic!

Rating: 4
Excellent. I added 1 clove of garlic instead of 3. Also, omitted the jalapeno since I didn't have any on hand. I had trouble forcing the puree thru our sieve - probably too small. Would serve chunky style next time to cut down on work. I think it's important to use only the freshest tomatoes you can find.

